INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'efc57974-e916-4dc3-aac4-5bb432e622be',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$wagmi Security — Phishing Signatures, Approval Exploits, and Why Your Frontend Holds No Keys$escape$,
  $escape$wagmi never exposes private keys — all signing is delegated to the injected wallet via `useSignMessage`, `useSignTypedData`, or `useSendTransaction`. Your dApp only constructs the payload; the wallet owns execution. The danger is what you put in that payload.

Signature phishing happens when a malicious site uses `useSignTypedData` with a crafted EIP-712 domain that mimics a trusted protocol. Always display the `domain.name` and `domain.verifyingContract` in your UI before calling `signTypedDataAsync` so users can verify the target contract.

Approval exploits are the bigger silent risk. Calling `useWriteContract` with `approve(spender, MaxUint256)` grants unlimited allowance. Instead, pass the exact token amount needed for the transaction. After the operation, prompt users to revoke via a follow-up `approve(spender, 0)` write. Use `useReadContract` to query current allowances before any approval flow — if `allowance >= amount`, skip the approve call entirely to avoid redundant exposure.

For `useSimulateContract`, always check the `request` object before executing — simulation catches revert scenarios but also reveals the exact calldata your user will sign.$escape$,
  $escape$import { useReadContract, useWriteContract, useSimulateContract } from 'wagmi'
import { erc20Abi, MaxUint256 } from 'viem'

const { data: allowance } = useReadContract({
  address: tokenAddress,
  abi: erc20Abi,
  functionName: 'allowance',
  args: [userAddress, spenderAddress],
})

const needsApproval = allowance !== undefined && allowance < requiredAmount

const { data: approveRequest } = useSimulateContract({
  address: tokenAddress,
  abi: erc20Abi,
  functionName: 'approve',
  args: [spenderAddress, requiredAmount], // never MaxUint256
  query: { enabled: needsApproval },
})

const { writeContract } = useWriteContract()
const handleApprove = () => approveRequest && writeContract(approveRequest.request)$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
